{
  "id": "rn_metric",
  "name": "Reissner-Nordström",
  "description": "The unique static, spherically symmetric vacuum solution to the Einstein-Maxwell equations describing the spacetime exterior to a charged, non-rotating mass.",
  "tags": [
    "vacuum",
    "static",
    "spherically symmetric",
    "charged",
    "black hole",
    "exact solution",
    "electrovacuum"
  ],
  "signature": "(-,+,+,+)",
  "convention": "The coordinate $r$ is the areal radius. The parameter $r_s = 2GM/c^2$ is the Schwarzschild radius and $r_q^2 = Q^2 G / (4\\pi\\epsilon_0 c^4)$ is the charge radius squared, where $Q$ is the total electric charge. The metric function is $\\Delta = r^2 - r_s r + r_q^2$. Horizons occur at $r_\\pm = \\dfrac{r_s}{2} \\pm \\sqrt{\\dfrac{r_s^2}{4} - r_q^2}$ when $r_s \\geq 2r_q$. Units with $c = 1$ are used throughout.",
  "history": "The charged generalization of the Schwarzschild metric arrived in pieces, and the story parallels the uncharged case almost beat for beat. In May 1916, Hans Reissner gave the gravitational field of a point charge — solving the Einstein equations in the presence of a Coulombic electric field [reissner1916]. His derivation used Schwarzschild's auxiliary radius $R$, so the solution was not yet in its modern form, and the structure of its singularities was interpreted through the same lens that had obscured Schwarzschild's. Nordström was himself no stranger to the problem of gravity — his scalar theory of gravitation had been a serious contender before Einstein's field equations settled the matter in 1915. Undeterred by that defeat, he turned to the new theory, and in 1918 did for Reissner's metric what Droste had done for Schwarzschild's: imposing isotropy directly on the auxiliary radius, he extended the areal coordinate to $r = 0$, giving the solution its modern form [nordstrom1918].¶The metric is characterized by two length scales: the Schwarzschild radius $r_s = 2GM/c^2$ and the charge radius, defined by $$r_q^2 = \\frac{Q^2 G}{4\\pi\\epsilon_0 c^4},$$ where $M$ is the mass and $Q$ the electric charge of the source. The metric admits up to two horizons, located at $$r_\\pm = \\frac{r_s}{2} \\pm \\sqrt{\\frac{r_s^2}{4} - r_q^2}.$$ These coalesce when $r_s = 2r_q$ in the extremal case, and become imaginary when the charge-to-mass ratio exceeds $\\sqrt{4\\pi\\epsilon_0 G}$. Nordström noted that the charge-to-mass ratios of the proton and electron far exceed this threshold, and used this to argue that the super-extremal regime represents elementary charged particles — elegantly banishing the horizons by phenomenological fiat. It wouldn't be until decades later that the super-extremal case was understood as a naked singularity, a violation of cosmic censorship [misner1973].¶The Ricci scalar vanishes identically for this metric, yet the Ricci tensor is nonzero — the spacetime is sourced entirely by the electromagnetic stress-energy of the field. The Reissner-Nordström metric is the unique static, spherically symmetric solution to the Einstein-Maxwell equations, and Einstein and Rosen later applied the same domain-extension trick to it as they had to the Schwarzschild metric, interpreting the two sheets of the geometry as positive and negative particles.",
  "references": [
    "reissner1916",
    "nordstrom1918",
    "misner1973"
  ],
